        "client_msg_id": "e741acd2-5810-43ad-a08c-028f3812a1d7",
        "text": "Seems worth highlighting Armstrong’s definitions of _error_ and _failure_.\n\nThe Erlang thesis starts with this sentence:\n\n&gt; How can we program systems which behave in a reasonable manner in the presence of software errors?\n\nThis begs the question of what an error is. The introductory chapters bounce between the terms ‘error’ and ‘fault’ or ‘failure’, which felt initially like a weakness of the exposition. I felt like I understood what was meant by ‘fault’ and ‘failure’ — the program crashes. So it felt overblown to generalize from crashes to all errors. But it all makes sense when I skip ahead to section 4.4, which defines ‘error’ like this:\n\n&gt; An error occurs when the programmer doesn’t know what to do.\n\nAnd the suggested response is the section title:\n\n&gt; Let the process crash.\n\nConcurrency provides the promise of turning all unanticipated situations into crashes. As long as the platform is equipped to detect and respond to crashes, this turns a hard problem into an easier one.",
        "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "user_team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "source_team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "user_profile": {
            "avatar_hash": "6e649a383cf8",
            "image_72": "https:\/\/avatars.slack-edge.com\/2019-07-14\/687915485201_6e649a383cf8f9e366e3_72.png",
            "first_name": "Kartik",
            "real_name": "Kartik Agaram",
            "display_name": "",
            "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
            "name": "ak",
            "is_restricted": false,
            "is_ultra_restricted": false
        },
        "thread_ts": "1555789502.005800",
        "parent_user_id": "U8A5MS6R1",
        "blocks": [
            {
                "type": "rich_text",
                "block_id": "Qhb2",
                "elements": [
                    {
                        "type": "rich_text_section",
                        "elements": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "Seems worth highlighting Armstrong’s definitions of "
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "error",
                                "style": {
                                    "italic": true
                                }
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": " and "
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "failure",
                                "style": {
                                    "italic": true
                                }
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": ".\n\nThe Erlang thesis starts with this sentence:\n\n"
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "rich_text_quote",
                        "elements": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "How can we program systems which behave in a reasonable manner in the presence of software errors?"
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "rich_text_section",
                        "elements": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "\n\nThis begs the question of what an error is. The introductory chapters bounce between the terms ‘error’ and ‘fault’ or ‘failure’, which felt initially like a weakness of the exposition. I felt like I understood what was meant by ‘fault’ and ‘failure’ — the program crashes. So it felt overblown to generalize from crashes to all errors. But it all makes sense when I skip ahead to section 4.4, which defines ‘error’ like this:\n\n"
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "rich_text_quote",
                        "elements": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "An error occurs when the programmer doesn’t know what to do."
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "rich_text_section",
                        "elements": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "\n\nAnd the suggested response is the section title:\n\n"
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "rich_text_quote",
                        "elements": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "Let the process crash."
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "rich_text_section",
                        "elements": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "\n\nConcurrency provides the promise of turning all unanticipated situations into crashes. As long as the platform is equipped to detect and respond to crashes, this turns a hard problem into an easier one."
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                ]
            }
        ],
